n students are in a line, having received grades at algorithms programming. They all must receive a candy at least, but those with a better grade than their neighbors should receive more than their respective neighbor. Minimum candy count?

Input:
a vector of floating-point numbers

Output:
minimum candy count

Solution (original):
dynamic programming is used. initially, all dp values are 1, then the 3 cases compute as follows:
ascending sequences make dp[i] = dp[i-1] + 1, stagnating make dp[i] = dp[i-1]. Then, decreasing sequences are the ones that add complexity:
the current student is assigned dp[i] = 1, while a for loop iterates backwards, reassigning values with dp[j] = dp[j + 1] + 1, until the hierarchy is met for the first time.

Complexity (original):
T: O(n) avg and O(n^2) worst-case for perfectly descending arrays
S: O(n) for an auxiliary dp vector

Solution (optimized):
two-pass greedy: forward (checking ascending or stagnating left to right) and backward (checking ascending or stagnating right to left, without overriding peaks)

Complexity (optimized):
T: O(n) every element is visited twice
S: O(n) for an auxiliary dp vector